    data$Min <- as.character(data$Min)
}

    data$Min <- as.character(data$Min)
}

Here we can notice that the second dimension is separating the players between exterior players and interior players. If we look at the stats, we can see that the ones that go up, represent the stats that are normally associated with centers or power forwards, such as blocks, scoring 2 points and offensive and defensive rebounds. On the oher hand, we can see that the ones that go down represent exterior players: three-pointers, free throws, assists,etc.

We have found the first dimension a little bit more difficult to interpret, but we think that this dimension separates between the attributes that contribute more for the personal stats, and the ones that contribute a lot for the whole team. The distribution between doubles and three-pointers is not really important for the whole team, and the steals dont matter that much. Nevertheless, defensive rebounds, fouls drawn and total points scored, are things that help a lot in a match for the whole team.

  1. Interpret variable plots. How can each dimension be named? As we said before, the first one is the contribution to the whole team, the second one is the sepparation between exterior and interior players.

We have spent a bit more time thinking about the third one and we think that this one can be related to the most and less variable stats. We can see that this dimension is separating between three-pointers and free throws (normally very consistent), and turnovers, assists and steals, that are stats that are a bit more random because they do not only depend on the skill of the player, but also on the circumstances. In the (2,3) relation, we can see that the exteriors are more consistent in free throws and three pointers, and the centers, with the rebounds, and that makes a lot of sense.

We do not know what dim4 and dim5 mean, as they explain quite less than the other dimensions.

Dim1 -> Here we can see the relation between good and bad players (in relation to the team contribution), because in the right zone of the plot there are highlighted players such as Laprovittola, Walter Tavares, Papanikolau, â¦

Dim2 -> Centers/Exteriors -> Walter,Hall,Fall / Sloukas, Papanikolau, Satoransky,â¦

Dim3 -> Now we can relate this dimension a little bit more accurately. It seems that this shows the accuracy of the player. If we look at the stats of George Papas, we can see that he has a 100% in three-pointers and free throws, nevertheless, he does not contribute that much to the team because he does not attempt to shoot that much, as he has aprox 3 points per game. On the other hand, we have Mike James. He is not that accurate, but as he throws a lot, he also makes a lot of points, and shooting a lot with a 45% in doubles and nearly a 30% in three-pointers is really a lot in the euroleague. For this reason, he ends contributing a lot more to the team that Papas, though having less accuracy.

Dim 4 -> We have made a discovery about this dimension. We think that this dimension can be called as âdirty workâ. We see that this dimension values a lot the steals. The fouls commited could be interpreted as a bad thing, but in this case, they are not. This is because committing fouls means that you are defending a lot and playing âdirtyâ, as we said. This also relates to the amount of free throws that you shoot, because if you are always there, you are going to be fouled by someone very often(though this dimension requires that you make these free throws). The same applies for the other way around, as we can see with the variable âblocks againstâ. This dimension also considers âthe amount of dirty work they are doing to youâ.

We have used the tactics of looking at the furthest individuals to find out what the dimensions mean, but for the fifth one everything is very regular, so we cannot know what this dimension is explaining.

  1. Interpret the plot.

Now we are distinguishing between the players but preserving the distance between these players. Though we are not taking into account the not numerical attributes such as position, we see that nonetheless, this plot is distinguishing between position. This implies that the numerical values have information very valuable to determine the position of the player. This is logic, because for example, the centers are going to get more rebounds and less three-pointers.

Apart from that, the ones that are more in the right part of the plot, are better players. The distance in the plot can be extrapolated to the difference between the real behaviours of the players. We can see that Walter Tavares is practically from another planet.

  1. Which MDS do you think better group the individuals? Why?

We think that gower is better because it does not make sense not to consider the position of the player when comparing them. We cannot compare a center with a pointguard because you do not care about a center not scoring three-pointers, and you do not care about a pointguard catching 12 rebounds per game either. For this reason, we think that gower distance is better in this case.
